Title: The Man in the High Castle
Author: Philip K Dick

Title: Small Giants
Subtitle: Companies That Choose to Be Great Instead of Big
Author: Bo Burlingham
Comment content:
Basically a collection of anecdotes this book makes for a nice read but the point is made about halfway and then repeated ad nauseum.

All in all you might get some good ideas from this though if your in the process of starting a business yourself or not getting much satisfaction out of your current one.

Title: Building Social Web Applications
Subtitle: Establishing Community at the Heart of Your Site
Author: Gavin Bell
Comment content: Both for experienced web developers or those just starting out building or designing social web apps this book offers a great summary of the many things you need to take into account. It offers both suggestions for your planning and design phase and best practices for building.

Title: The Lord of the Rings
Subtitle: Part 1: The Fellowship of the Ring; Part 2: The Two Towers; Part 3: The Return of the King
Author: J.R.R. Tolkien

Subtitle: (Vintage)
Author: Dave Eggers

Subtitle: And Other Clinical Tales
Author: Oliver Sacks

Subtitle: A Novel About the History of Philosophy
Author: Jostein Gaarder

Title: A Short History of Nearly Everything
Author: Bill Bryson

Author: Mark Haddon

Title: The Hitch Hiker's Guide to the Galaxy
Author: Douglas Adams

Author: J. K. Rowling

Title: Nexus
Subtitle: Small Worlds and the Groundbreaking Theory of Networks
Author: Mark Haddon, Mark Buchanan

Title: Guns, Germs and Steel
Subtitle: A short history of everybody for the last 13,000 years
Author: Jared Diamond

Title: High Performance MySQL
Author: Balling Derek J., Jeremy D. Zawodny

Title: Somberman's actie
Author: Remco Campert
Publisher: Stichting Collectieve Propaganda van het Nederlandse Boek

Title: Stupid White Men
Subtitle: ...and Other Sorry Excuses for the State of the Nation
Author: Michael Moore

Title: Kuifje / 14 kuifje en het zwarte goud
Author: Herge

Title: De avonturen van Kuifje / De zonnetempel
Author: Herge

Author: Herge

Author: Herge

Author: Herge

Title: After Dark - A Format
Author: Haruki Murakami
Comment content: Totally unlike any other novel i've ever read when it comes to style. Reminiscent of Japanese cinema when it comes to story.

Title: Halting State
Author: Charles Stross
Comment content: Charles Stross mixes up hip tech such as augmented reality, ubiquitous computing and virtual worlds to create an believable and exciting near future backdrop to this funny and fast paced crime novel.

Title: A spot of bother
Author: Mark Haddon
Comment content: sometimes slightly unnerving but mostly touching and funny. although quite unlike my own family it did somehow feel familiar.

Title: Debatable Space
Author: Philip Palmer
Comment content: Invokes a universe with an epic scale on par with star wars but does so with a sense of humor. Space pirates with existential angst.

Title: Little Brother
Author: Cory Doctorow
Comment content:
While i was slightly annoyed with the many sidetracks and explanations in the beginning this book ended up really sucking me in.

It does a great job of illustrating the thornier issues of security technology. If you ever wonder how all this tech might affect your day to day life this is a must read. Freedom vs. Security and all that jive.

Title: Good Omens
Subtitle: The Nice and Accurate Prophecies of Agnes Nutter, Witch
Author: Terry Pratchett, Neil Gaiman
Comment content: entertaining read but not very remarkable

Title: Everyware
Subtitle: The Dawning Age of Ubiquitous Computing
Author: Adam Greenfield
Comment content: For some reason i had a hard time finishing this one, got distracted by other books a lot. Eventually i must conclude this is a good read though and especially worthwhile if you have any interest in the concept of ubiquitous computing. It summarizes most of what has been going on in this field up until 2004 and adds some rather evocative questions every designer of everywhere should ask his- or himself.

Title: After Tamerlane
Subtitle: The Rise and Fall of Global Empires, 1400-2000
Author: John Darwin

Title: Dress Your Family in Corduroy and Denim
Author: David Sedaris

Title: Building Scalable Web Sites
Subtitle: Building, Scaling, and Optimizing the Next Generation of Web Applications
Author: Cal Henderson

Title: The Black Swan
Subtitle: The Impact of the Highly Improbable
Author: Nassim Nicholas Taleb
Comment content: Taleb is not the best writer ever and some of his less-likable character traits come through in his writing and might put you off a bit in the beginning. But hang in there and you'll be sure to get convinced his theories are sound and find yourself a little smarter in the end.

Title: Shakespeare
Subtitle: The World as a Stage
Author: Bill Bryson
Comment content: Great little book. For the gossipy tales of shakespearean england and the gossipy tales of shakespearean historians. This book is very much a fun read, as most of Bryson's books tend to be.

Title: Blind Faith
Author: Ben Elton
Comment content: rambles on a bit. it's a horrific but funny sort of future vision but told with much lack of subtlety.

Title: Geisha of Gion
Author: Mineko Iwasaki
Comment content: Interesting insight into one of the more mysterious parts of Japans cultural heritage.

Title: Prey
Author: Michael Crichton
Comment content: pseudo scientific horror story about creepy crawlers of the nano variety.

Title: Anansi Boys
Author: Neil Gaiman
Comment content: Awesome tale of love, growing up and a whole lot of other stuff rolled up in a big and lovingly created fantasy story. Fantasy on a literary level though not the childish swords and dragons stuff.

Title: Neverwhere
Subtitle: The Author's Preferred Text
Author: Neil Gaiman
Comment content: Less intelligent than some of his other books but still highly entertaining. Reads like a nice fantasy tv series somewhere along the lines of dr who.

Title: Programming Google App Engine
Author: Dan Sanderson
Comment content: Seems its rather outdated. Every time I picked this up to look up a problem at hand it was incomplete or just wrong. Reads like someone copy pasted the official docs with some minor tweaks here and there.
